 1. What is multithreading and why is it used?
 ============================================================
 -> A thread is a small part of program .Think of like multiple worker doing different task at the same time.
 -> Multithreading is a concept that we can execute one or more parts of program simultaneously.
 
    Why Multithreading is Used
   -----------------------------------
   1. Improves Performance
   2. Better Resource Utilization
   3. Handles Multiple Tasks Simultaneously
   4. Improves User Experience
   
 2. Difference between process and thread
 ============================================================
 -> Process is an independent program, while thread is a part of a process that runs tasks inside it.
    Process: An independent program in execution.
    Thread: A lightweight unit of execution inside a process.
 -> Process has its own memory space.
    Thread share the memory with other thread.
 -> Process is independent.
    Thread depend on process.
 -> If one process crash then it doesn't affect other process.
    But if one thread is crash then it affect to the entire process.
 -> Inside one process there is multiple thread is present.
 
	 Process 1        Process 2
	   |                |
	 ---------      ---------
	 | T1 T2 |      | T1 T2 |
	 ---------      ---------
 
 3. Difference between Thread and Runnable
 ===============================================================
 -> Thread 👉 A class used to create and run a thread
 -> Runnable 👉 An interface used to define the task for a thread
	| Feature     | Thread                                             | Runnable                                      |
	| ----------- | -------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
	| Type        | Class                                              | Interface                                     |
	| Purpose     | Create & run thread                                | Define task only                              |
	| Inheritance | Cannot extend another class (Java allows only one) | Can extend another class + implement Runnable |
	| Recommended | ❌ Not preferred                                    | ✅ Preferred                                   |
	 
 EX:
  Using Thread Class
 ---------------------------------------------------
		 class MyThread extends Thread {
		    public void run() {
		        System.out.println("Thread class running");
		    }
		
		    public static void main(String[] args) {
		        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();
		        t1.start();   // start thread
		    }
		}

 Using Runnable Interface (Recommended)
 --------------------------------------------------
		class MyTask implements Runnable {
		    public void run() {
		        System.out.println("Runnable running");
		    }
		
		    public static void main(String[] args) {
		        MyTask task = new MyTask();
		        Thread t1 = new Thread(task);
		        t1.start();   // start thread
		    }
		}

 4. What is the thread lifecycle in Java?
 ========================================================================
  ->  NEW → RUNNABLE → RUNNING → WAITING/BLOCKED → TERMINATED
  
   - NEW
        Thread is created but not started
        Thread t = new Thread();
     
   - RUNNABLE
        Thread is ready to run (after calling start())
        Waiting for CPU
        
   - RUNNING
        Thread is currently executing run() method
        
   - WAITING / BLOCKED
        Thread is paused temporarily
        Waiting for another thread (wait(), join())
        
   - TERMINATED
        Thread has finished execution
        
		NEW 
		 ↓ (start)
		RUNNABLE 
		 ↓ (CPU assigned)
		RUNNING 
		 ↓ (wait/sleep)
		WAITING/BLOCKED 
		 ↓
		RUNNING 
		 ↓
		TERMINATED	
		
 5.  What is context switching?
 ===============================================================
 -> Context Switching is the process where the CPU switches from one thread (or process) to another.
 -> CPU can run only one thread at a time
 -> So it quickly switches between threads to give a feeling of parallel execution
 Ex:
    Imagine:
        Thread 1 → doing calculation
        Thread 2 → reading file
    CPU does:
        Thread 1 → Thread 2 → Thread 1 → Thread 2 ...
        
 6. What is a daemon thread?
 ================================================================
 -> A Daemon Thread is a background thread that runs to support main tasks of an application.
 -> It is a background thread that automatically terminates when all user threads finish execution.
 Ex:
    User Thread → important work (main task)
    Daemon Thread → helper/background work
       Ex:: Garbage collection (JVM)
            Background logging
            Auto-save
            
		class MyDaemon extends Thread {
		    public void run() {
		        while (true) {
		            System.out.println("Daemon thread running...");
		        }
		    }
		
		    public static void main(String[] args) {
		        MyDaemon t = new MyDaemon();
		        t.setDaemon(true);   // make it daemon
		        t.start();
		
		        System.out.println("Main thread finished");
		    }
		}
		
		O/p
		   Main thread finished
           Daemon thread running... (may stop anytime)
           
 7. What is thread priority? Does it guarantee execution?
 ======================================================================
 -> Thread priority is a number that tells the CPU which thread should get preference for execution.
 -> Thread priority is a hint to the scheduler about execution, but it does not guarantee that higher priority threads will execute first.
 Ex:
	Thread t1 = new Thread();
	Thread t2 = new Thread();
	
	t1.setPriority(2);   // low priority
	t2.setPriority(8);   // high priority
	
 8.What is synchronization and why is it needed?
 =========================================================================
  -> Synchronization is a mechanism used to control access of multiple threads to shared resources so that only one thread can access it at a time.
  -> When multiple threads work on the same data, synchronization makes sure they don’t interfere with each other.
  -> Through Synchronization we can maintain the data consistency in multithread environment.
  
 9. Difference between synchronized method and synchronized block
 =========================================================================
 -> Synchronized Method 👉 locks the entire method
 -> Synchronized Block 👉 locks only a specific part of code
 
	| Feature     | Synchronized Method       | Synchronized Block              |
	| ----------- | ------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
	| Lock Scope  | Whole method              | Only selected block             |
	| Performance | Slower (locks everything) | Faster (locks only needed part) |
	| Flexibility | Less flexible             | More flexible                   |
	| Lock Object | Uses `this` (by default)  | Can use any object              |
	| Usage       | Simple cases              | Complex / optimized cases       |
	
 10.  What is an intrinsic lock (monitor)?
 ============================================================================
 -> An Intrinsic Lock (Monitor) is an internal lock mechanism that every object in Java has, used to control access in synchronization.
 Ex:
		Thread 1 → gets lock → executes
		Thread 2 → waits
		Thread 1 → releases lock
		Thread 2 → gets lock → executes
		
 11.  What is a deadlock? How can you prevent it?
 ==============================================================================
 -> A deadlock is a situation where two or more threads are stuck forever, waiting for each other to release resources.
	Thread 1 → holds Lock A, waiting for Lock B  
	Thread 2 → holds Lock B, waiting for Lock A
 -> Prevent DeadLock
    - Use Same Lock Order
		Thread 1 → Lock A → Lock B  
		Thread 2 → Lock A → Lock B
    - Avoid Nested Locks
    - Timeout Mechanism
    
 12.  What is a race condition?
 ============================================================================
 -> A race condition occurs when multiple threads access and modify shared data at the same time, and the final result depends on which thread runs first.
 -> In that case data inconsistency is happening.
 
 13. What is thread starvation?
 =============================================================================
 -> Thread starvation happens when a thread does not get CPU time or resources for a long time because other threads keep getting preference.
 -> The thread is ready to run but keeps waiting indefinitely ❌
 Ex:
	Thread A → high priority
	Thread B → low priority
	
	CPU keeps executing Thread A
	Thread B waits continuously → Starvation
	
 14. What is livelock?
 ============================================================================
 -> A livelock is a situation where threads are not blocked, but they keep changing their state continuously and still can’t complete their work.
 Ex:
    Threads keep “responding” to each other
    But never finish the task
    
	Thread 1 → "You go first"
	Thread 2 → "No, you go first"
	Thread 1 → "Okay, you go"
	Thread 2 → "No, you go"
	
 15. comparison of Deadlock vs Livelock vs Starvation
 ============================================================================
 
	| Feature              | Deadlock                   | Livelock                     | Starvation                  |
	| -------------------- | -------------------------- | ---------------------------- | --------------------------- |
	| **State of Threads** | Blocked (stuck)            | Active (moving)              | Waiting                     |
	| **Progress**         | ❌ No progress             | ❌ No progress               | ❌ Very slow / none          |
	| **CPU Usage**        | Low (threads idle)         | High (continuous activity)   | Depends                     |
	| **Cause**            | Circular waiting for locks | Overreaction between threads | Unfair scheduling           |
	| **Example**          | Lock A ↔ Lock B            | “You go first” loop          | Low priority thread ignored |
	
 16. What are wait(), notify(), and notifyAll()?
 ===========================================================================
 -> These methods are used for inter-thread communication.
 -> They are defined in the Object class
    1. wait()
    -------------------------
    -> Makes the current thread pause and release the lock
    -> Thread goes into waiting state
    
    2. notify()
    ------------------------
    -> Wakes up one waiting thread
    
    3. notifyAll()
    ------------------------
    -> Wakes up all waiting threads
    
 17. Difference between wait() and sleep()
 ==========================================================================
		| Feature | `wait()`                      | `sleep()`                |
		| ------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------ |
		| Class   | `Object` class                | `Thread` class           |
		| Lock    | ✅ Releases lock              | ❌ Does NOT release lock  |
		| Purpose | Inter-thread communication    | Pause execution          |
		| Wake-up | By `notify()` / `notifyAll()` | Automatically after time |
		| Usage   | Inside synchronized block     | Anywhere                 |
		
 18.  Why must wait() be called inside a synchronized block?
 ============================================================================
 -> wait() must be called inside a synchronized block because the thread needs to own the object’s lock before
    it can release it and enter the waiting state.		
    
    Internal Logic
    -------------------------
    Thread enters synchronized block → gets lock
    Calls wait() →
          releases lock
          goes to waiting state
          
          
 19. What happens if notify() is called before wait()?
 ===========================================================================
 -> If notify() is called before wait(), the notification is lost because no thread is waiting at that time,
    which may cause the waiting thread to block indefinitely.
  Ex:
    📢 Teacher announces:
      “Class is over, you can go!”   
      
      👉 But no students are in class
      
      Later students come and wait…
      👉 They never get the message → stuck waiting
      
      
 20.  What is ExecutorService? Why is it preferred over Thread?
 ===============================================================================
 -> ExecutorService is a thread pool framework used to manage and execute tasks efficiently, and it is preferred over Thread
    because it provides thread reuse, better performance, task management, and result handling.
 -> Executor is an interface used to run tasks.
 -> ExecutorService is an advanced version of Executor.
 
  Types of ExecutorService
  ----------------------------------------------
  1. newFixedThreadPool()
        - Fixed number of threads
        - ExecutorService ex = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5);
        
  2. newCachedThreadPool()
        - It creates threads depends on the CPU.
        - ExecutorService ex = Executors.newCachedThreadPool();
  
  3. newSingleThreadExecutor()
        - It create only one thread.
        - ExecutorService ex = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();
        
  4. newScheduledThreadPool()
        - It run task in specific time.
        - ScheduledExecutorService ex = Executors.newScheduledThreadPool(2);
        
  5. newWorkStealingPool()
        - Uses multiple queues, balances load
        - ExecutorService ex = Executors.newWorkStealingPool();
        
        
 21. What is a thread pool? Types of thread pools
 ==================================================================================
 -> A Thread Pool is a collection of pre-created threads used to execute multiple tasks.
 -> ThreadPoolExecutor is the core implementation behind ExecutorService
 -> It manages a pool of reusable worker threads to execute tasks efficiently.
 
  Types of Thread Pools
  -----------------------------------
  1. FixedThreadPool
  2. CachedThreadPool
  3. SingleThreadExecutor	
  4. ScheduledThreadPool
  5. WorkStealingPool
 
