	    int maximumPoolSize,
	    long keepAliveTime,
	    TimeUnit unit,
	    BlockingQueue<Runnable> workQueue,
	    ThreadFactory threadFactory,
	    RejectedExecutionHandler handler
	   )
		
 22. Difference between submit() and execute()
 ============================================================================
	| Aspect                 | `execute()`                                          | `submit()`                                      |
	| ---------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
	| **Defined In**         | `Executor` interface                                 | `ExecutorService` interface                     |
	| **Return Type**        | `void`                                               | `Future<?>`                                     |
	| **Result Handling**    | ❌ Cannot return result                              | ✅ Can return result (`Callable`)                |
	| **Task Type**          | `Runnable` only                                      | `Runnable` and `Callable`                       |
	| **Exception Handling** | Exception is thrown immediately (visible in console) | Exception is captured inside `Future`           |
	| **Tracking Task**      | ❌ Not possible                                       | ✅ Possible using `Future` (`isDone()`, `get()`) |
	| **Use Case**           | Fire-and-forget tasks                                | Tasks where result/status is needed             |

	 execute()	
			ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
			executor.execute(() -> {
			    System.out.println("Task executed");
			});
		
	 submit()
			ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
			Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(() -> {
			    return 10 + 20;
			});
			
			System.out.println(future.get()); // 30

 23. What is Future?
 =============================================================================
 -> Future is an interface used to represent the result of an asynchronous task.
 -> It acts like a promise that the result will be available later.
  Ex:
		ExecutorService ex = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
		
		Future<Integer> future = ex.submit(() -> {
		    return 10 + 20;
		});
		
		System.out.println(future.get()); // 30
		
		ex.shutdown();

 24. What is CompletableFuture?
 ==============================================================================
 -> CompletableFuture is an enhanced of Future interface that supports asynchronous task execution, Chain multiple tasks,
    combining dependent tasks, and exception handling.
    
 Ex:
		CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "Java")
		    .thenApply(s -> s + " Developer")
		    .thenAccept(System.out::println); 
		    
	| Feature            | Future | CompletableFuture |
	| ------------------ | ------ | ----------------- |
	| Get Result         | ✅     | ✅                |
	| Chain Tasks        | ❌     | ✅                |
	| Combine Tasks      | ❌     | ✅                |
	| Callback           | ❌     | ✅                |
	| Exception Handling | Basic  | Powerful          |
	
 25. Difference between synchronous and asynchronous execution
 ================================================================================
 -> Synchronous 👉 One task at a time, wait until current task finishes.
 -> Asynchronous 👉 Start task and continue other work without waiting.
 
	| Aspect      | Synchronous           | Asynchronous                   |
	| ----------- | --------------------- | ------------------------------ |
	| Execution   | Sequential            | Independent / parallel style   |
	| Waiting     | Yes                   | No immediate wait              |
	| Blocking    | Blocking              | Non-blocking                   |
	| Performance | Slower for long tasks | Better for I/O or long tasks   |
	| Complexity  | Simple                | More complex                   |
	| Example     | Normal method call    | `CompletableFuture`, callbacks |
	
 26. What is the volatile keyword?
 ===================================================================================
 -> volatile is a keyword used in multithreading to make a variable’s latest value visible to all threads immediately.
 -> If one thread changes the variable, other threads can see the updated value directly.
 
 27.  Difference between volatile and synchronized
 ==================================================================================
 -> Both are used in multithreading, but they solve different problems.
 -> volatile 👉 Ensures latest value is visible to all threads
 -> synchronized 👉 Controls access so only one thread uses resource at a time
 
    volatile = visible
    synchronized = safe access
    
 28. What is the happens-before relationship?
 ==================================================================================
 -> The happens-before relationship is a rule in the Java Memory Model (JMM) that guarantees:
 -> If Action A happens-before Action B, then
    all changes made in A are visible to B, and A executes before B in terms of memory consistency.
    
 29. What are atomicity, visibility, and consistency?
 =================================================================================
  1. Atomicity
     - All the operation treated as a single unit, means all the operation is done or fail.
     
  2. Visibility
     - When one thread updates a variable, other threads must see the latest value.
     
  3. Consistency
     - Data remains correct and predictable across threads.
     
